% mmap_spi.nw -- QUADSPI memory-mapped (FMODE=11) wall-rate
% chapter.

== Why this chapter exists

The indirect-read path (MDMA over `QUADSPI->DR`) tops out near
337 Mbps quad on this rig (`spi_simple` quad mission, presc=3
sshift=0, single-pass). The bottleneck is the per-word AXI
handshake the MDMA pays on every FIFO drain --- empirically
~3 ACLK cycles per byte, additive with the SCLK byte time, and
not configurable through CK_QSPI / HCLK6 / TLEN / SBURST /
FTHRES. See the root-cause table in `agent4/TODO.md`.

Memory-mapped mode (FMODE=11) is one of three documented escape
hatches. In FMODE=11 the QUADSPI peripheral autonomously refills
its prefetch buffer in response to AHB reads from the
`QSPI_MM_BASE` window (0x70000000); the master only needs to
issue reads. Iter 1 proved end-to-end correctness with a byte-by-
byte CPU loop --- but that variant is dominated by single-byte
AHB read latency and clocked at 36.63 Mbps, an order of magnitude
under the quad-MDMA floor.

Iter 2 broadens the read master into a parameterised sweep so the
firmware-side bottleneck is measurable independently of the
peripheral. A new optional variant argument selects the copy
strategy without recompiling between runs:

- `H <len> 0`: byte-by-byte CPU loop (regression baseline).
- `H <len> 1`: 32-bit word CPU loop (`uint32_t *` cast).
- `H <len> 2`: `memcpy` with non-volatile aliases (LDM/STM).
- `H <len> 3`: MDMA mem-to-mem from `QSPI_MM_BASE` into DDR.

The MDMA variant is the headline experiment: with a 64 B per-
buffer transfer (16 beats of 32-bit), 16-beat source/dest
bursts and software request mode, every per-byte AHB handshake
the indirect path paid is hidden behind a 16-beat AXI read of the
QSPI peripheral's prefetch buffer. If that works the wall-rate
should comfortably clear the 337 Mbps quad ceiling.

== Test plan

Single FPGA program (`qspi.bin`, the existing 0x6B Quad Output
Read slave). The DUT firmware is the agent4 baremetal/qspi build
that exposes the new `H <len> <variant>` command. After bringup
to the proven quad mission point (`p 3 0`, prescaler 3, sshift
0), four `H` invocations run in MDMA-first order:

. `H 1048576 3` -- mission-target MDMA path, gates `>337 Mbps`.
. `H 1048576 2` -- `memcpy` aliases, gates `>100 Mbps`.
. `H 1048576 1` -- 32-bit word loop, gates `>75 Mbps`.
. `H 1048576 0` -- byte loop regression check, relaxed to
  `>30 Mbps` (iter 1 measured 36.63).

The MDMA block runs FIRST so the most informative result lands
in the UART log even if a later block aborts the suite (`make
test` halts on the first failing block, so blocks past the first
failure are not executed).

Each `H` invocation prints a single summary line of the form

  mmap <bytes> B quad in <ms> ms, <X.YZ> Mbps, presc=<p>,
  qspi_hz=<hz>, variant=<v>[, cisr=..., cesr=...]

The verifier picks the LAST line whose `variant=<v>` matches the
block's expected variant; that way each block stays independent
even though all four lines share the same `mmap` prefix.

Cap is 16 MiB (one DDR slot at `DEF_DDR_BASE`); 1 MiB amortises
prefetch warmup while staying under the 120 s expect timeout
even if MDMA misbehaves.

